You can generate a table of contents (TOC) automatically in a LaTeX document using the `table of contents` facility provided by the document class and the `toc` package (which is loaded by default by most classes). Here's a minimal example:

```latex
\documentclass{book} % or \documentclass{report} or \documentclass{article}
\begin{document}

\tableofcontents

\chapter{Introduction}
Text of chapter one

\section{First section}
Text of first section

\section{Second section}
Text of second section

\subsection{Subsection}
Text of subsection

\chapter{Main Results}
Text of chapter two

\section{Important Finding}
Text of important finding

\backmatter
\appendix
\section{Appendix}
Appendix content

\end{document}
```

In this example, the `\tableofcontents` command is used to generate the table of contents. LaTeX will automatically detect the sectioning commands (`\chapter`, `\section`, `\subsection`, etc.) and generate the TOC entries.

When you run LaTeX (e.g., `pdflatex` or `xelatex`) on this document, it will generate a table of contents at the position of the `\tableofcontents` command. The TOC will list all the sectioning elements in the document, formatted accordingly to the document class's style.

Note that if you want to customize the appearance or behavior of the TOC, you can use packages like `tocloft`, `tocstyle`, or `etoc`, which offer more advanced features. However, for basic automatic generation, the built-in LaTeX feature is sufficient.

